WEBVTT - https://subtitletools.com

00:00:01.067 --> 00:00:05.138
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:00:05.138 --> 00:00:06.173
[PHONE RINGS]

00:00:06.173 --> 00:00:12.179
-EMERGENCY. KERRY SPEAKING.

00:00:12.179 --> 00:00:13.113
HE'S HERE?

00:00:13.113 --> 00:00:18.819
[AMBULANCE SIREN WAILS]

00:00:18.819 --> 00:00:19.787
-OKAY, GUYS.
THEY'RE HERE.

00:00:19.787 --> 00:00:21.020
-WORKING
IN THE EMERGENCY DEPARTMENT,

00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:23.924
EVERY DAY
IT'S A LITTLE DIFFERENT.

00:00:23.924 --> 00:00:29.763
[BUSTLE OF WORKERS
IN CONVERSATION]

00:00:29.763 --> 00:00:35.035
-BASICALLY, A STAB WOUND
TO THE RIGHT CHEST.

00:00:35.035 --> 00:00:36.003
NO OTHER INJURIES

00:00:36.003 --> 00:00:37.838
APART FROM
THE SUPERFICIAL INJURIES

00:00:37.838 --> 00:00:38.605
TO THE CHEST.

00:00:38.605 --> 00:00:41.675
THAT'S ABOUT A 10-INCH BLADE,
SERRATED,

00:00:41.675 --> 00:00:44.311
AND IT'S BURIED
AT LEAST TWO INCHES.

00:00:44.311 --> 00:00:45.679
-OH, MY GOD.

00:00:45.679 --> 00:00:46.881
[LOUD CHATTER]

00:00:46.881 --> 00:00:48.248
-OKAY, GUYS.
LET'S KEEP IT DOWN.

00:00:48.248 --> 00:00:50.083
-GUYS, WE NEED TO KEEP
THE NOISE DOWN, PLEASE, HUH?

00:00:50.083 --> 00:00:54.287
-I THINK ALL OF US,
OUR ADRENALIN GOES A LITTLE BIT.

00:00:54.287 --> 00:00:56.423
BUT IT IS ALWAYS SURPRISING
WHEN YOU SEE SOMEONE COME IN

00:00:56.423 --> 00:00:57.992
AND THE KNIFE IS STILL IN PLACE.

00:00:57.992 --> 00:01:01.461
-CAN YOU TELL ME YOUR NAME?

00:01:01.461 --> 00:01:02.095
-ARE YOU OKAY?

00:01:02.095 --> 00:01:03.998
DO YOU UNDERSTAND
WHAT'S GOING ON?

00:01:03.998 --> 00:01:05.699
ARE YOU IN A LOT OF PAIN?

00:01:05.699 --> 00:01:07.868
-IF YOU'RE AIMING A KNIFE
STRAIGHT FOR THE HEART,

00:01:07.868 --> 00:01:10.136
YOU'RE ATTEMPTING TO DO
SIGNIFICANT HARM.

00:01:10.136 --> 00:01:14.541
-WIGGLE YOUR FINGERS
ON THIS SIDE.

00:01:14.541 --> 00:01:15.475
...MY FINGER.

00:01:15.475 --> 00:01:18.311
SQUEEZE MY FINGER.
SQUEEZE. SQUEEZE MY FINGER.

00:01:18.311 --> 00:01:21.048
-GIVEN WHERE THE KNIFE
WAS STICKING OUT,

00:01:21.048 --> 00:01:22.516
HE WAS REMARKABLY STABLE.

00:01:22.516 --> 00:01:23.717
NOW, WHETHER THAT'S JUST BECAUSE

00:01:23.717 --> 00:01:25.151
THE KNIFE DIDN'T GO IN
FAR ENOUGH,

00:01:25.151 --> 00:01:26.687
WE'LL FIND OUT.

00:01:26.687 --> 00:01:29.656
-OKAY, WE'LL GET YOU
TO SQUIRT IT OUT.

00:01:29.656 --> 00:01:32.091
-SO REMOVING ANY KNIFE
RIGHT NOW

00:01:32.091 --> 00:01:33.360
IS THE WRONG DECISION.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:34.394
HE'S GOING UP
TO THE OPERATING ROOM,

00:01:34.394 --> 00:01:37.631
AND THAT'S WHERE IT'S
THE SAFEST PLACE TO TAKE IT OUT.

00:01:37.631 --> 00:01:50.210
-THERE'S NO TYPICAL DAY
IN EMERGENCY.

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:54.982
[AMBULANCE SIREN WAILS]

00:01:54.982 --> 00:02:04.091
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:02:04.091 --> 00:02:06.894
-THE NEXT OF KIN,
EMERGENCY CONTACT?

00:02:06.894 --> 00:02:12.032
-UH, CAN IT BE MATT?

00:02:12.032 --> 00:02:13.968
-LET ME GO THROUGH
YOUR BLOODWORK

00:02:13.968 --> 00:02:19.138
AND WE'LL TAKE IT FROM THERE,
OKAY?

00:02:19.138 --> 00:02:19.740
-AAH!

00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:20.774
-THAT'S SORE THERE, HEY?
-YEAH.

00:02:20.774 --> 00:02:22.109
-WHAT MAKES OUR JOB
REALLY NEAT

00:02:22.109 --> 00:02:24.143
HERE
AT VANCOUVER GENERAL HOSPITAL

00:02:24.143 --> 00:02:24.778
IS THE VARIETY.

00:02:24.778 --> 00:02:27.881
SO WE SEE YOUNG PEOPLE,
WE SEE ELDERLY PEOPLE.

00:02:27.881 --> 00:02:29.282
WE MIGHT GO
FROM SEEING A PATIENT

00:02:29.282 --> 00:02:30.383
WHO IS SUFFERING FROM A STROKE

00:02:30.383 --> 00:02:32.886
AND THEN MOVE ON AND SEE
SOMEBODY WITH A ROLLED ANKLE.

00:02:32.886 --> 00:02:35.856
WE NEVER REALLY KNOW
WHAT'S COMING IN NEXT.

00:02:35.856 --> 00:02:37.791
-LOWER IT DOWN A BIT.
NICE AND LOUD.

00:02:37.791 --> 00:02:39.927
-THE PEOPLE THAT I WORK WITH
ARE FANTASTIC.

00:02:39.927 --> 00:02:40.794
THEY'RE A BIG PART OF THE REASON

00:02:40.794 --> 00:02:43.097
WHY I ENJOY WORKING HERE
SO MUCH.

00:02:43.097 --> 00:02:45.165
-OPEN YOUR EYES.
LOOK AT ME.

00:02:45.165 --> 00:02:46.033
HI.

00:02:46.033 --> 00:02:47.200
[SLOWLY] CALM DOWN.

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:48.635
IT TAKES A SPECIAL KIND
OF PERSON

00:02:48.635 --> 00:02:51.071
TO WORK FULL-TIME IN EMERG
FOR SURE.

00:02:51.071 --> 00:02:53.440
YOU HAVE TO THINK ON YOUR FEET
AND PROBLEM-SOLVE,

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:56.576
AND YOU DON'T MIND IT
WHEN THINGS GET SUPER-WACKY

00:02:56.576 --> 00:02:59.446
AND YOU DON'T SIT DOWN
FOR 12 HOURS STRAIGHT.

00:02:59.446 --> 00:03:00.480
-OPEN YOUR EYES.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:03.017
THIS IS YOUR LAST CHANCE
BEFORE WE PUT A BREATHING TUBE.

00:03:03.017 --> 00:03:05.886
ONE OF THE LESSONS YOU LEARN
IN THE EMERGENCY DEPARTMENT

00:03:05.886 --> 00:03:08.022
IS HOW UNPREDICTABLE LIFE IS.

00:03:08.022 --> 00:03:08.789
IT CAN TRULY TURN

00:03:08.789 --> 00:03:11.125
AND CHANGE DRAMATICALLY
ON A DIME,

00:03:11.125 --> 00:03:12.392
AND IN AN INSTANT.

00:03:12.392 --> 00:03:13.027
WE WITNESS PEOPLE

00:03:13.027 --> 00:03:15.529
WHOSE LIVES GET TURNED
COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN

00:03:15.529 --> 00:03:16.864
AT A MOMENT'S NOTICE,

00:03:16.864 --> 00:03:34.614
AND WE GET TO BE THERE
FOR THEM.

00:03:34.614 --> 00:03:40.654
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:03:40.654 --> 00:03:41.755
-JONATHAN?
-MM-HMM.

00:03:41.755 --> 00:03:43.190
DO YOU GO BY JOE
OR BY JONATHAN?

00:03:43.190 --> 00:03:43.891
-JONATHAN.
-OKAY.

00:03:43.891 --> 00:03:46.193
[CELL PHONE RINGS]
-OH, THAT'S MY MOM.

00:03:46.193 --> 00:03:49.529
IT'S JUST...

00:03:49.529 --> 00:03:51.932
I'LL PICK IT UP LATER.

00:03:51.932 --> 00:03:53.167
-DO YOU MIND JUST...
-YEP.

00:03:53.167 --> 00:03:54.034
-IT'S JUST LIDOCAINE.

00:03:54.034 --> 00:03:55.635
SO I'M JUST GOING
TO PUT THIS ON HERE

00:03:55.635 --> 00:03:57.604
JUST FOR A SECOND.

00:03:57.604 --> 00:03:58.605
SO WE HAVE A YOUNG GENTLEMAN

00:03:58.605 --> 00:04:01.008
THAT HAS SOMETHING CALLED
ATRIAL FIBRILLATION,

00:04:01.008 --> 00:04:03.677
WHERE THE HEART
IS BEATING IRREGULARLY.

00:04:03.677 --> 00:04:04.811
-THIS MORNING, I WOKE UP,

00:04:04.811 --> 00:04:08.182
AND IT'S AS IF I RAN,
LIKE, A MARATHON OR SOMETHING.

00:04:08.182 --> 00:04:09.716
MY HEART WAS JUST GOING OFF.

00:04:09.716 --> 00:04:11.651
[FAST BEEPING]

00:04:11.651 --> 00:04:15.089
SO USUALLY A HEARTBEAT'S BY...
IT GOES BUMP, BUMP, BUMP, BUMP.

00:04:15.089 --> 00:04:17.124
RIGHT NOW, APPARENTLY
IT GOES BOOM-BOOM,

00:04:17.124 --> 00:04:19.960
BOOM-BOOM-BOOM, BOOM-BOOM,
BOOM-BOOM-BOOM.

00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:22.863
[BEEPING]

00:04:22.863 --> 00:04:24.330
-WE TYPICALLY DON'T WANT PEOPLE

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:26.433
TO REMAIN IN THIS IRREGULAR
HEART RHYTHM

00:04:26.433 --> 00:04:28.001
FOR A PROLONGED PERIOD OF TIME,

00:04:28.001 --> 00:04:30.904
SO WE'RE GOING TO USE
ELECTRICITY

00:04:30.904 --> 00:04:34.608
TO CHANGE HIS HEART RHYTHM
FROM THIS IRREGULAR

00:04:34.608 --> 00:04:38.678
BACK INTO A NORMAL RHYTHM.

00:04:38.678 --> 00:04:41.949
-THOSE ARE THE PADS THAT WILL
GIVE YOU THE LITTLE SHOCK, OKAY?

00:04:41.949 --> 00:04:43.150
-OKAY.

00:04:43.150 --> 00:04:43.784
THEY KNOCK ME OUT

00:04:43.784 --> 00:04:46.220
AND SHOCK MY HEART
BACK TO NORMAL.

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:47.854
-LET'S PUT THIS ON YOUR FINGER.

00:04:47.854 --> 00:04:48.922
-OKAY.

00:04:48.922 --> 00:04:54.360
-IT'S A PRETTY SCARY CONCEPT,
AND WHAT THE RISK FACTORS ARE,

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:55.762
WHAT COULD GO WRONG?

00:04:55.762 --> 00:04:58.598
WE COULD GIVE THEM ENTIRELY
WAY TOO MUCH MEDICATION

00:04:58.598 --> 00:05:02.202
AND COMPLETELY PUT YOU TO SLEEP
TO THE POINT OF VIEW

00:05:02.202 --> 00:05:02.936
THAT YOU STOP BREATHING.

00:05:02.936 --> 00:05:08.441
THEN THERE'S A WHOLE BUNCH
OF RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH THAT.

00:05:08.441 --> 00:05:10.144
-YOU'VE HAD THIS DONE BEFORE.

00:05:10.144 --> 00:05:11.078
-NO.

00:05:11.078 --> 00:05:11.745
-OKAY.

00:05:11.745 --> 00:05:13.880
SO WE'RE GOING TO GIVE YOU
SOME SEDATION SOON, OKAY?

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:17.151
-HE SEEMS ACTUALLY QUITE BLASE
ABOUT IT,

00:05:17.151 --> 00:05:19.385
MORE SO THAN I WOULD BE.

00:05:19.385 --> 00:05:23.056
-OKAY, SO WE'RE GOING TO PUT YOU
TO SLEEP, OKAY?

00:05:23.056 --> 00:05:31.165
IT MIGHT STING
IN THE ARM A LITTLE BIT.

00:05:31.165 --> 00:05:32.199
-MOVE YOUR HEAD DOWN A LITTLE.

00:05:32.199 --> 00:05:33.700
-HOW ARE YOU FEELING THERE?

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:38.005
-I'M FEELING WOOZY AND DIZZY.

00:05:38.005 --> 00:05:42.109
-[MONITOR BEEPING,
CONVERSATIONS IN BACKGROUND]

00:05:42.109 --> 00:05:46.280
-HOW ARE YOU DOING, JONATHAN?

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:47.914
-OKAY, LET'S CHARGE.

00:05:47.914 --> 00:05:49.183
-EVERYONE CLEAR.

00:05:49.183 --> 00:05:51.651
[MACHINE MAKES
HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

00:05:51.651 --> 00:05:56.256
[STEADY TONE]

00:05:56.256 --> 00:05:57.991
[THUMP OF DEFIBRILLATION]

00:05:57.991 --> 00:06:02.863
[MONITOR BEEPING]

00:06:02.863 --> 00:06:09.602
-DEEP BREATH IN, JONATHAN.

00:06:09.602 --> 00:06:12.539
ALL RIGHT, BIG BREATH IN.

00:06:12.539 --> 00:06:15.008
BIG BREATH IN.

00:06:15.008 --> 00:06:18.578
-DEEP BREATH, JONATHAN.

00:06:18.578 --> 00:06:20.714
-BIG BREATH, BIG BREATH.

00:06:20.714 --> 00:06:23.416
JONATHAN?

00:06:23.416 --> 00:06:24.784
OH, THERE YOU GO.

00:06:24.784 --> 00:06:27.287
-SLOWLY COMING TO.

00:06:27.287 --> 00:06:29.956
-CAN YOU GIVE US A THUMBS UP?

00:06:29.956 --> 00:06:31.390
SWEET.

00:06:31.390 --> 00:06:32.492
WE'LL SIT YOU UP.

00:06:32.492 --> 00:06:33.093
-THERE WE GO.

00:06:33.093 --> 00:06:36.462
-HE GOT MAYBE A LITTLE BIT
TOO MUCH SLEEP MEDICATION.

00:06:36.462 --> 00:06:37.964
WE HAD TO YELL AT HIM
A FEW TIMES

00:06:37.964 --> 00:06:40.600
TO REMIND HIM TO BREATHE,
WHICH HE DID.

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:43.036
-JONATHAN. ALL DONE.

00:06:43.036 --> 00:06:44.571
-YOU'RE ALL DONE?

00:06:44.571 --> 00:06:45.872
-ALL DONE, YEAH.

00:06:45.872 --> 00:06:48.008
-HOW LONG WAS I OUT?

00:06:48.008 --> 00:06:48.942
-EIGHT MINUTES?

00:06:48.942 --> 00:06:50.344
-OH, OKAY.
-NOT LONG.

00:06:50.344 --> 00:06:53.513
-THE PATIENT CAN GO HOME
HALF AN HOUR, AN HOUR LATER

00:06:53.513 --> 00:06:58.885
AFTER THE PROCEDURE.

00:06:58.885 --> 00:07:01.588
SO, YOUR HEART, DOES IT FEEL
ANY DIFFERENT NOW?

00:07:01.588 --> 00:07:02.722
-ACTUALLY, IT'S MUCH BETTER.

00:07:02.722 --> 00:07:04.858
IT DOESN'T FEEL THAT STRESS
THAT, LIKE,

00:07:04.858 --> 00:07:06.293
AFTER YOU DID A LONG RUN

00:07:06.293 --> 00:07:08.095
OR, LIKE... HEARTBURN STRESS.

00:07:08.095 --> 00:07:11.164
-HE'S A LITTLE YOUNG TO HAVE
THIS ATRIAL FIBRILLATION.

00:07:11.164 --> 00:07:13.466
HE'S GOT TO FOLLOW UP
WITH A NEUROLOGIST

00:07:13.466 --> 00:07:14.534
TO TRY AND FIGURE OUT

00:07:14.534 --> 00:07:16.903
WHY EXACTLY HE HAD
THESE SYMPTOMS.

00:07:16.903 --> 00:07:29.049
-I'M GLAD I'M BACK TO NORMAL,
I GUESS, RECOVERING.

00:07:29.049 --> 00:07:44.197
[AMBULANCE SIREN WAILS]

00:07:44.197 --> 00:07:47.267
-OKAY, PATIENT'S HERE.

00:07:47.267 --> 00:07:49.136
PULL THE CURTAINS,
THERE, SOMEBODY.

00:07:49.136 --> 00:07:50.536
THANK YOU.

00:07:50.536 --> 00:07:52.372
-WE'LL GO.
-YEAH.

00:07:52.372 --> 00:07:55.942
-SENSE OF HUMOUR IN THE ER,
I THINK, IS ESSENTIAL.

00:07:55.942 --> 00:07:56.542
WE MAKE A JOKE

00:07:56.542 --> 00:07:58.345
THAT WE'RE ESSENTIALLY
PREVENTING DARWINISM,

00:07:58.345 --> 00:08:01.348
BUT THERE'S SOME ELEMENT
OF TRUTH TO THAT.

00:08:01.348 --> 00:08:03.783
IT'S HARD TO SAY
THE DUMBEST THING I'VE SEEN.

00:08:03.783 --> 00:08:05.118
THERE ARE A LOT OF PEOPLE
OUT THERE

00:08:05.118 --> 00:08:14.627
THAT AREN'T VERY BRIGHT.

00:08:14.627 --> 00:08:17.230
-SHE WAS ON SOME MONKEY BARS
AT A PLAYGROUND.

00:08:17.230 --> 00:08:20.499
FLIPPED BACKWARDS...

00:08:20.499 --> 00:08:22.501
-THE EMERGENCY DEPARTMENT
ATTRACTS A LOT OF PEOPLE

00:08:22.501 --> 00:08:24.938
THAT ARE DOING,
FOR WHATEVER REASON,

00:08:24.938 --> 00:08:26.106
VERY SILLY THINGS.

00:08:26.106 --> 00:08:29.276
-FLIPPED BACKWARDS,
LOST HER GRIP, FELL BACK,

00:08:29.276 --> 00:08:30.410
BANGED HER ARM,

00:08:30.410 --> 00:08:32.812
AND THEN HEARD A SNAP,
ROLLED BACK.

00:08:32.812 --> 00:08:34.714
SHE THINKS SHE MAY HAVE STRUCK
HER HEAD.

00:08:34.714 --> 00:08:41.154
NO NECK PAIN OR BACK PAIN
RIGHT NOW.

00:08:41.154 --> 00:08:42.389
-SO THE EXTENT OF HER INJURIES

00:08:42.389 --> 00:08:47.794
ARE AN OPEN HUMERUS FRACTURE
HERE.

00:08:47.794 --> 00:08:49.262
-AND SHE'S BEEN SICK.

00:08:49.262 --> 00:08:50.364
-WHAT ARE YOU DOING
CLIMBING MONKEY BARS

00:08:50.364 --> 00:08:52.932
AT A QUARTER AFTER MIDNIGHT
ON A FRIDAY NIGHT?

00:08:52.932 --> 00:08:56.536
-[WHISPERING] SHE'S DRUNK.

00:08:56.536 --> 00:08:58.071
-YOU KNOW, INITIALLY,
YOU NEVER KNOW

00:08:58.071 --> 00:08:59.306
WHAT YOU'RE GOING TO GET

00:08:59.306 --> 00:09:05.912
WHEN THE PATIENT ROLLS
THROUGH THE DOOR.

00:09:05.912 --> 00:09:07.280
-SHE OBVIOUSLY
HAD AN ARM INJURY,

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:10.050
BUT WE'RE LOOKING
FOR THE LIFE-THREATENING THINGS,

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:11.818
INJURIES THAT MAY NOT BE
THAT OBVIOUS,

00:09:11.818 --> 00:09:14.054
SO LUNGS, THE HEART,
THE ABDOMEN,

00:09:14.054 --> 00:09:15.621
THE C SPINE OR NECK.

00:09:15.621 --> 00:09:18.691
-AND ONE MORE TIME,
BIG BREATH IN, AND HOLD IT.

00:09:18.691 --> 00:09:20.394
SO WE'RE LOOKING
AT YOUR INTERNAL ORGANS

00:09:20.394 --> 00:09:22.595
TO JUST MAKE SURE
THERE'S NO BLEEDING IN THERE.

00:09:22.595 --> 00:09:23.397
-OKAY.

00:09:23.397 --> 00:09:26.433
-OUR JOB IS REALLY
TO RUN THROUGH OUR PROTOCOL

00:09:26.433 --> 00:09:27.133
AND JUST MAKE SURE

00:09:27.133 --> 00:09:28.935
THAT WE'RE RULING
THOSE THINGS OUT

00:09:28.935 --> 00:09:31.505
AND MAKING SURE SHE'S STABLE.

00:09:31.505 --> 00:09:36.109
[QUIET DISCUSSION]

00:09:36.109 --> 00:09:37.744
SO, AT THE END,
WE'RE LEFT WITH INJURIES

00:09:37.744 --> 00:09:41.647
THAT ARE MORE MANAGEABLE.

00:09:41.647 --> 00:09:45.352
-NOW MOVE YOUR HAND
BACK AND FORTH.

00:09:45.352 --> 00:09:48.021
CAN YOU MOVE YOUR WRIST
BACK AND FORTH?

00:09:48.021 --> 00:09:49.856
OKAY, SORRY ABOUT THAT.

00:09:49.856 --> 00:09:54.294
YOU OKAY THERE?

00:09:54.294 --> 00:09:55.562
-WE GOT ULTRASOUNDS, X-RAYS.

00:09:55.562 --> 00:09:57.730
NOTHING ELSE WE CAN IDENTIFY,
SO WE'RE PRETTY CONFIDENT

00:09:57.730 --> 00:10:00.066
THAT THERE'S NO LIFE-THREATENING
INJURIES HERE.

00:10:00.066 --> 00:10:03.203
SHE'S GOING TO HAVE TO HAVE
AN OPERATION TO FIX HER ARM,

00:10:03.203 --> 00:10:04.471
TO REPAIR THIS AND WASH IT OUT,

00:10:04.471 --> 00:10:09.008
AND MAKE SURE
IT DOESN'T GET INFECTED.

00:10:09.008 --> 00:10:10.944
-SO, WAS THIS
A FALLING ACCIDENT TOO?

00:10:10.944 --> 00:10:12.312
IS THIS A FAMILY THING?

00:10:12.312 --> 00:10:14.080
FALLING OUT OF THINGS.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:17.984
-THEY RECOGNIZE THEY'VE DONE
SOMETHING INCREDIBLY STUPID.

00:10:17.984 --> 00:10:19.886
-SO ARE YOU DOING ALL RIGHT?
-YEAH.

00:10:19.886 --> 00:10:21.821
-HAVING THE ABILITY TO LAUGH

00:10:21.821 --> 00:10:23.390
AND SAY,
"YOU'RE GOING TO BE OKAY,"

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:24.924
THAT GOES A LONG WAY
TO REASSURING THEM

00:10:24.924 --> 00:10:25.825
AND MAKING THEM FEEL BETTER.

00:10:25.825 --> 00:10:28.495
PLUS, YOU'VE GOT TO HAVE FUN
AT WORK.

00:10:28.495 --> 00:10:36.536
[ER RECEPTION CHATTER]

00:10:36.536 --> 00:10:40.607
-DR. McKNIGHT,
WILL YOU BE MY VALENTINE?

00:10:40.607 --> 00:10:47.914
[GIGGLING]

00:10:47.914 --> 00:10:48.948
-WHAT DID YOU DO, MY DEAR?

00:10:48.948 --> 00:10:50.850
-FELL OFF OF A CLIMBING WALL.

00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:51.751
-OFF OF A CLIMBING WALL.

00:10:51.751 --> 00:10:54.087
-AND THEN JUST--
THE ANKLE WENT UNDER.

00:10:54.087 --> 00:10:56.156
-SO DID THEY THINK
IT WAS DISLOCATED?

00:10:56.156 --> 00:10:58.057
-HE DIDN'T REALLY SAY
WHAT HE THOUGHT.

00:10:58.057 --> 00:10:59.759
-OKAY, SO JUST YOUR FOOT DOWN.

00:10:59.759 --> 00:11:01.995
YOU'RE NOT GOING TO WEIGHT-BEAR
AT ALL ON THE OTHER.

00:11:01.995 --> 00:11:02.862
EXCELLENT. GOOD JOB.

00:11:02.862 --> 00:11:06.065
-THEY WERE ROCK CLIMBING
FOR VALENTINE'S DAY.

00:11:06.065 --> 00:11:07.100
WHO DOES THAT?

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:09.235
ISN'T THERE, LIKE, CHOCOLATES
AND FLOWERS

00:11:09.235 --> 00:11:10.570
AND DINNER INVOLVED?

00:11:10.570 --> 00:11:12.071
-CAN YOU SCOOT YOURSELF UP?
-YEP.

00:11:12.071 --> 00:11:12.639
-WE CLIMB A LOT,

00:11:12.639 --> 00:11:13.873
SO IT WAS JUST LIKE,
"LET'S GO CLIMBING.

00:11:13.873 --> 00:11:17.076
MAYBE IT WON'T BE BUSY
ON VALENTINE'S DAY."

00:11:17.076 --> 00:11:18.911
-DID THE AMBULANCE
BRING YOU IN?

00:11:18.911 --> 00:11:21.848
-YEAH, THEY DID.
YEAH, THEY WERE REALLY GOOD.

00:11:21.848 --> 00:11:23.116
-CAN YOU WIGGLE
YOUR TOES FOR ME?

00:11:23.116 --> 00:11:24.484
DOES THAT HURT?
-YEP.

00:11:24.484 --> 00:11:26.219
-OKAY, WHERE IS THE PAIN?

00:11:26.219 --> 00:11:29.489
-THE PAIN
IS ALL WHERE SHE'S LOOKING.

00:11:29.489 --> 00:11:33.660
-ANY FEELING HERE?
DO YOU HAVE ANY PAIN HERE?

00:11:33.660 --> 00:11:34.227
-NO.
-OKAY.

00:11:34.227 --> 00:11:36.429
DO YOU HAVE ANY PAIN UP HERE?
-OH! YEAH!

00:11:36.429 --> 00:11:37.397
-YOU DO HAVE PAIN HERE?

00:11:37.397 --> 00:11:39.799
-BUT WHEN YOU DID THAT,
IT JUST SENT IT SHOOTING THERE.

00:11:39.799 --> 00:11:40.600
-DO YOU HAVE SOME PAIN HERE?

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:43.136
BECAUSE DID YOU COME DOWN
LIKE THIS ON IT?

00:11:43.136 --> 00:11:46.939
-I CAME DOWN, I THINK,
STRAIGHT,

00:11:46.939 --> 00:11:48.308
AND THEN WHOA, YEAH.

00:11:48.308 --> 00:11:49.643
IT WAS MY LAST ROUTE

00:11:49.643 --> 00:11:50.843
THAT I WAS GOING TO DO
OF THE NIGHT,

00:11:50.843 --> 00:11:51.678
AND I ALMOST DIDN'T GO ON,

00:11:51.678 --> 00:11:54.247
AND WAS LIKE,
"OH, I'LL TRY ONE MORE TIME.

00:11:54.247 --> 00:11:55.048
MAYBE I'LL GET IT."

00:11:55.048 --> 00:11:56.816
AND, LIKE, MY HAND POPPED OFF.

00:11:56.816 --> 00:11:59.018
MY FOOT ENDED UP COMING
UNDERNEATH ME,

00:11:59.018 --> 00:12:01.087
SO THEN IT WAS LIKE POP, POP.

00:12:01.087 --> 00:12:01.921
-TRY TO PLANT YOUR FOOT.

00:12:01.921 --> 00:12:04.624
I WANT YOU TO TAKE YOUR FOOT
AND POINT IT DOWN.

00:12:04.624 --> 00:12:05.592
CAN YOU?

00:12:05.592 --> 00:12:08.595
[SHE WHIMPERS IN PAIN]

00:12:08.595 --> 00:12:10.830
IT'S OKAY.
CAN YOU PULL IT UP TOWARDS YOU?

00:12:10.830 --> 00:12:11.964
-NO.
-OKAY.

00:12:11.964 --> 00:12:14.534
DO YOU HAVE ANY PAIN IN HERE?

00:12:14.534 --> 00:12:16.670
-NO.
-OKAY.

00:12:16.670 --> 00:12:19.172
-THEY ENDED UP CALLING
THE AMBULANCE,

00:12:19.172 --> 00:12:20.540
AND IT WAS EMBARRASSING.

00:12:20.540 --> 00:12:23.510
I HAD TO LEAVE ON A STRETCHER,
AND EVERYONE WAS LIKE,

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:25.744
"WHAT'S HAPPENING TO HER?"

00:12:25.744 --> 00:12:27.847
AND THE FIRST TIME
I'D EVER BEEN IN AN AMBULANCE.

00:12:27.847 --> 00:12:29.716
WAS IT THE FIRST TIME
YOU'VE BEEN IN AN AMBULANCE,

00:12:29.716 --> 00:12:30.584
MATT?

00:12:30.584 --> 00:12:32.018
-UH, YEAH, IT WAS.

00:12:32.018 --> 00:12:34.254
-YEAH?
IT WAS A MERCEDES.

00:12:34.254 --> 00:12:35.788
-I TOOK HER FOR A RIDE
IN A MERCEDES

00:12:35.788 --> 00:12:37.323
ON VALENTINE'S DAY.

00:12:37.323 --> 00:12:45.432
-YEAH, EXACTLY.

00:12:45.432 --> 00:12:52.905
THANK YOU.

00:12:52.905 --> 00:13:02.315
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:13:02.315 --> 00:13:04.384
-A LOT OF WHAT YOU DO
IN ANY JOB

00:13:04.384 --> 00:13:05.585
DOES BECOME A BIT ROUTINE,

00:13:05.585 --> 00:13:07.153
SO YOU'RE LOOKING
FOR THOSE THINGS

00:13:07.153 --> 00:13:07.887
THAT ARE NOT ROUTINE,

00:13:07.887 --> 00:13:10.022
THOSE THINGS THAT KEEP YOU
INTERESTED IN THE JOB.

00:13:10.022 --> 00:13:12.459
I THINK THE CASES MOST OF US
LOOK FORWARD TO THE MOST

00:13:12.459 --> 00:13:14.327
ARE THE CRITICALLY ILL PATIENTS.

00:13:14.327 --> 00:13:15.729
THOSE ARE THE MOST INTERESTING,

00:13:15.729 --> 00:13:17.930
AND GIVE YOU A BIT
OF THE ADRENALIN SHOT.

00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:23.236
THOSE ARE THE MOST EXCITING ONES
TO DEAL WITH.

00:13:23.236 --> 00:13:23.869
-YEAH, I KNOW,

00:13:23.869 --> 00:13:26.872
BUT WE'RE GOING TO TAKE REALLY
GOOD CARE OF YOU, THOUGH, OKAY?

00:13:26.872 --> 00:13:27.774
-SHE'S A YOUNG WOMAN.

00:13:27.774 --> 00:13:30.443
SHE HAD A SKI ACCIDENT,
WAS SEEN IN THE CLINIC,

00:13:30.443 --> 00:13:40.320
WAS TRANSFERRED DOWN.

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:42.722
-WE WERE TOLD
THAT SHE WAS VERY STABLE,

00:13:42.722 --> 00:13:44.457
AND SHE WAS.

00:13:44.457 --> 00:13:47.494
-SO WE'RE GOING TO DO
SOME TESTS, OKAY?

00:13:47.494 --> 00:13:48.227
-THE STORY YOU GET

00:13:48.227 --> 00:13:49.228
WHEN THE PATIENTS
ARE TRANSFERRED DOWN

00:13:49.228 --> 00:13:52.231
IS NOT OFTEN WHAT HAPPENS
WHEN THEY GET HERE.

00:13:52.231 --> 00:13:54.200
THINGS CHANGE OVER TIME.

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:55.669
-ARE YOU DOING ALL RIGHT?

00:13:55.669 --> 00:13:57.003
-ANY OF THE TRANSFER PATIENTS,

00:13:57.003 --> 00:13:59.905
THE EMERG DOCS TEND TO EYEBALL
WHEN THEY GET HERE,

00:13:59.905 --> 00:14:02.342
JUST TO MAKE SURE
EVERYTHING'S STABLE

00:14:02.342 --> 00:14:03.643
AND THEY'RE OKAY.

00:14:03.643 --> 00:14:05.345
WHEN I WENT TO CHECK ON HER,

00:14:05.345 --> 00:14:13.353
INSTANTLY I KNEW SHE WASN'T.

00:14:13.353 --> 00:14:17.691
SHE'S LOOKING WHITE
AS A GHOST.

00:14:17.691 --> 00:14:18.491
SHE WAS VERY PALE,

00:14:18.491 --> 00:14:20.426
AND HER BLOOD PRESSURE
WAS DROPPING.

00:14:20.426 --> 00:14:21.160
-RIGHT WHEN SHE GOT HERE,

00:14:21.160 --> 00:14:22.495
IT LOOKS
LIKE HER SPLEEN HAD RUPTURED,

00:14:22.495 --> 00:14:25.965
AND SO SHE STARTED BLEEDING
QUITE FREELY

00:14:25.965 --> 00:14:27.166
INTO HER ABDOMEN.

00:14:27.166 --> 00:14:29.703
SO SHE ENDED UP
NOT BEING WELL AT ALL

00:14:29.703 --> 00:14:31.170
AND VERY SICK.

00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:31.838
[BEEP]

00:14:31.838 --> 00:14:34.407
-WE STARTED GIVING HER BLOOD
RIGHT OFF THE BAT.

00:14:34.407 --> 00:14:37.310
IT'S IMPORTANT TO TRY
AND GET HER BLOOD VOLUMES UP

00:14:37.310 --> 00:14:39.045
AND TRY AND RESUSCITATE HER
QUICKLY.

00:14:39.045 --> 00:14:41.180
WE'RE JUST GOING TO GET YOU
SOME PAINKILLERS, OKAY?

00:14:41.180 --> 00:14:43.750
JUST SQUEEZE MY HAND
IF IT'S GETTING BAD, OKAY?

00:14:43.750 --> 00:14:47.353
SHE'S A YOUNG WOMAN.
SHE WAS JUST PRETTY SCARED.

00:14:47.353 --> 00:14:49.422
I KNOW THERE'S A LOT OF STUFF
BEEPING,

00:14:49.422 --> 00:14:51.190
AND ON TV, BEEPING'S BAD.

00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:54.093
DOWN HERE,
WE KIND OF IGNORE IT A LOT.

00:14:54.093 --> 00:14:54.994
[MONITOR BEEPING]

00:14:54.994 --> 00:14:57.697
ONCE YOU SEE US LOOKING WORRIED,
THEN YOU CAN WORRY.

00:14:57.697 --> 00:14:58.665
[CHATTER AND DISCUSSION]

00:14:58.665 --> 00:15:00.500
-IT CAN BE LIFE-THREATENING,
FOR CERTAIN.

00:15:00.500 --> 00:15:09.442
OH, YEAH.
NO, IT'S VERY SERIOUS.

00:15:09.442 --> 00:15:10.176
WE'RE TRYING TO DECIDE

00:15:10.176 --> 00:15:12.445
EXACTLY WHETHER WE SHOULD
TAKE HER TO THE CT SCANNER

00:15:12.445 --> 00:15:14.514
AND SCAN HER TO LOOK
AT THE EXTENT OF THE INJURY,

00:15:14.514 --> 00:15:17.450
OR WHETHER SHE'S TOO SICK
TO HAVE THAT PROCEDURE DONE,

00:15:17.450 --> 00:15:19.619
AND TO GO STRAIGHT
TO THE OPERATING ROOM.

00:15:19.619 --> 00:15:32.899
-WE'RE GOING TO REASSESS?

00:15:32.899 --> 00:15:33.833
-90% OF THE TIME,

00:15:33.833 --> 00:15:35.602
PEOPLE COME IN
WITH NO DIAGNOSIS,

00:15:35.602 --> 00:15:37.437
SO YOU'RE STARTING FROM SCRATCH,

00:15:37.437 --> 00:15:38.571
YOU DON'T HAVE A LOT
OF INFORMATION,

00:15:38.571 --> 00:15:40.907
YOU DON'T HAVE A RELATIONSHIP
WITH THE PATIENT

00:15:40.907 --> 00:15:41.908
OR KNOW THEIR BACKGROUND.

00:15:41.908 --> 00:15:44.176
YOU'RE REALLY TRYING TO GATHER
THOSE INFORMATION BITS

00:15:44.176 --> 00:15:47.914
AND MAKE A DECISION VERY QUICKLY
IN TERMS OF WHAT'S WRONG

00:15:47.914 --> 00:16:00.359
AND WHAT COULD BE
LIFE-THREATENING.

00:16:00.359 --> 00:16:02.528
-I'VE JUST STARTED WORKING
AT VGH.

00:16:02.528 --> 00:16:05.964
I CAME FROM A SMALL COMMUNITY
HOSPITAL EMERGENCY,

00:16:05.964 --> 00:16:07.400
SO IT'S COMPLETELY DIFFERENT.

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:09.535
IT'S LIKE TWO DIFFERENT
EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS,

00:16:09.535 --> 00:16:12.238
AND I'VE COME FROM A CENTRE
THAT DOESN'T RECEIVE TRAUMA.

00:16:12.238 --> 00:16:15.575
BEING TAUGHT HOW TO HANDLE
A TRAUMA WHEN IT COMES IN

00:16:15.575 --> 00:16:16.709
IS A BIT DIFFERENT

00:16:16.709 --> 00:16:19.512
WHEN IT ACTUALLY SHOWS UP
AT YOUR FEET

00:16:19.512 --> 00:16:21.213
AND YOU HAVE TO DEAL WITH IT.

00:16:21.213 --> 00:16:23.817
-YOU'RE DOING OKAY, ALL RIGHT?
JUST KEEP BREATHING.

00:16:23.817 --> 00:16:26.786
YOU LET US KNOW
IF YOU HAVE TOO MUCH PAIN.

00:16:26.786 --> 00:16:29.021
[MONITORS BEEP]

00:16:29.021 --> 00:16:31.624
AH, SO SHE'S HAD TWO OF THESE?

00:16:31.624 --> 00:16:34.193
-THIS IS THE THIRD
GOING IN NOW.

00:16:34.193 --> 00:16:36.028
SHE HAD BLED SO MUCH

00:16:36.028 --> 00:16:41.501
THAT SHE'S NO LONGER ABLE
TO SUPPORT HER BLOOD PRESSURE.

00:16:41.501 --> 00:16:43.803
BASICALLY, YOU'VE GOT PIPES.
THEY NEED TO BE FULL OF BLOOD.

00:16:43.803 --> 00:16:45.505
SO WHEN YOU LOSE BLOOD
INTO THE ABDOMEN,

00:16:45.505 --> 00:16:46.673
THERE'S NOT BLOOD GOING ANYWHERE
ELSE.

00:16:46.673 --> 00:16:51.611
UNLESS YOU TREAT IT QUICKLY,
IT CAN GET PRETTY BAD.

00:16:51.611 --> 00:16:53.479
-I THINK ALL OF US
IN THE EMERGENCY DEPARTMENT

00:16:53.479 --> 00:16:55.782
HAVE HAD SHIFTS
THAT HAVE SCARED US,

00:16:55.782 --> 00:16:58.284
WHERE YOU WIND UP
WITH A VERY SICK PATIENT.

00:16:58.284 --> 00:17:00.586
THE JOB ENTAILS
A LOT OF TOUGH DECISIONS.

00:17:00.586 --> 00:17:03.756
SOMETIMES
YOU'RE GOING TO BE WRONG.

00:17:03.756 --> 00:17:06.492
[MONITOR BEEPING;
LOW HUM OF DISCUSSION]

00:17:06.492 --> 00:17:20.006
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:17:20.006 --> 00:17:21.641
-WE THINK
SHE'S NOT STABLE ENOUGH

00:17:21.641 --> 00:17:22.608
TO GO TO THE CT SCANNER.

00:17:22.608 --> 00:17:23.877
WE'RE GOING STRAIGHT
TO THE OPERATING ROOM.

00:17:23.877 --> 00:17:25.945
-SO WE'RE MAKING
THE CALL FOR THE OR.

00:17:25.945 --> 00:17:26.846
-OKAY.
-ARE YOU?

00:17:26.846 --> 00:17:28.347
-YEAH.
-FOR A LAP?

00:17:28.347 --> 00:17:30.717
-LAPAROTOMY'S SET UP,
TRAUMA LAP.

00:17:30.717 --> 00:17:38.992
-ALL RIGHT. HERE WE GO.

00:17:38.992 --> 00:17:39.659
-WHEN YOU OPERATE,

00:17:39.659 --> 00:17:41.494
VERY OFTEN, YOU HAVE TO ACTUALLY
TAKE THE SPLEEN OUT,

00:17:41.494 --> 00:17:50.870
BUT I'M HOPING BEYOND HOPE
WE CAN SAVE THE SPLEEN.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:52.238
-WE'RE GOING TO HAVE TO OPEN
HER UP,

00:17:52.238 --> 00:17:58.344
FIND THE SOURCE OF THE BLEEDING,
CONTROL THAT.

00:17:58.344 --> 00:18:01.948
-OH, REALLY?

00:18:01.948 --> 00:18:03.416
-SHE'S ALREADY ON IT.

00:18:03.416 --> 00:18:04.316
-SHE'S A YOUNG WOMAN.

00:18:04.316 --> 00:18:05.451
SHE'S GOT A LOT GOING FOR HER

00:18:05.451 --> 00:18:07.987
IN TERMS OF THE PREDICTORS
OF A POSITIVE OUTCOME,

00:18:07.987 --> 00:18:11.824
SO MY GUESS IS
SHE'LL DO WELL.

00:18:11.824 --> 00:18:12.859
-THIS CASE IS SIGNIFICANT

00:18:12.859 --> 00:18:15.528
BECAUSE
THAT WAS MY FIRST TRAUMA,

00:18:15.528 --> 00:18:16.729
ACTUALLY, AS AN RN,

00:18:16.729 --> 00:18:19.565
SO THAT WAS VERY STRESSFUL
FOR ME.

00:18:19.565 --> 00:18:22.234
I HAD TO START USING EVERYTHING
I'D BEEN TAUGHT

00:18:22.234 --> 00:18:23.669
IN FRONT OF OTHER PEOPLE, YEAH,

00:18:23.669 --> 00:18:26.338
NOT JUST GOING OVER IT
IN MY HEAD.

00:18:26.338 --> 00:18:27.807
I THOUGHT IT WENT REALLY WELL.

00:18:27.807 --> 00:18:28.908
IT'S THE PERFECT BABY STEP

00:18:28.908 --> 00:18:34.380
IN THE DIRECTION
OF TRAUMA NURSING AT VGH.

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:39.552
[SIREN WAILS]

00:18:39.552 --> 00:18:42.588
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:18:42.588 --> 00:18:44.023
-INTOXICATED.

00:18:44.023 --> 00:18:44.757
-YEAH, SHE'S VERY DRUNK.

00:18:44.757 --> 00:18:46.893
SHE STARTED DOING THE GESTURES
AND VOMITING,

00:18:46.893 --> 00:18:49.996
AND VOMITED IN HER HANDS
AND THEN SWALLOWED IT.

00:18:49.996 --> 00:18:52.264
-NICE.
WHY WASTE IT?

00:18:52.264 --> 00:18:52.865
[LAUGHS]

00:18:52.865 --> 00:18:54.033
-AND THEN I GAVE HER A BUCKET
AND SAID,

00:18:54.033 --> 00:18:55.768
"DON'T YOU PUKE ON MY FLOOR,"

00:18:55.768 --> 00:18:57.036
AND GAVE HER THE BUCKET.

00:18:57.036 --> 00:18:59.338
-CAN YOU CALL IT VOMIT
IF YOU SWALLOW IT AGAIN?

00:18:59.338 --> 00:19:13.586
-YOU KNOW, THAT TAKES TALENT
TO SWALLOW YOUR OWN VOMIT.

00:19:13.586 --> 00:19:17.957
-I CAME IN BECAUSE I SLICED
MY FINGER REALLY BAD.

00:19:17.957 --> 00:19:19.892
-OKAY, LET'S HAVE A LOOK.

00:19:19.892 --> 00:19:21.894
OH, YOU DID A GOOD JOB THERE,
EH?

00:19:21.894 --> 00:19:23.629
YOU JUST NEED SOME STITCHES.

00:19:23.629 --> 00:19:24.597
-YES.

00:19:24.597 --> 00:19:28.101
I WAS AT HOME, OPENING UP
SOME PLASTIC PACKAGING,

00:19:28.101 --> 00:19:31.270
AND LIKE I TELL MY DAUGHTER
ALL THE TIME

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:33.572
TO USE THE SCISSORS,

00:19:33.572 --> 00:19:34.740
I WAS USING A KNIFE,

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:37.777
AND I PROCEEDED TO STAB MYSELF
IN THE FINGER

00:19:37.777 --> 00:19:40.212
AND CUT IT RIGHT DOWN
ALMOST TO THE BONE,

00:19:40.212 --> 00:19:43.049
WHICH IS NOT COOL.

00:19:43.049 --> 00:19:44.483
IT COULD HAVE BEEN
TOTALLY AVOIDED

00:19:44.483 --> 00:19:45.818
IF I'D USED SCISSORS.

00:19:45.818 --> 00:19:48.387
-SO IS YOUR DAUGHTER
DOING OKAY OUT THERE?

00:19:48.387 --> 00:19:53.026
-I BELIEVE SHE'S DOING FINE.

00:19:53.026 --> 00:19:54.627
-DID THEY DELIVER
TO THE ER HERE?

00:19:54.627 --> 00:19:57.030
-THEY DELIVERED, ACTUALLY,
PIZZA TO THE ER.

00:19:57.030 --> 00:19:57.930
I WAS QUITE AMAZED.

00:19:57.930 --> 00:20:00.399
-MY MIDDLE DAUGHTER
IS AROUND THE SAME AGE...

00:20:00.399 --> 00:20:00.867
-OKAY.

00:20:00.867 --> 00:20:03.302
-AND SHE'S REALLY FASCINATED
BY THIS STUFF.

00:20:03.302 --> 00:20:04.971
-MY DAUGHTER IS TOO, ACTUALLY.

00:20:04.971 --> 00:20:06.472
SHE WANTED TO SEE
WHAT I'D DONE.

00:20:06.472 --> 00:20:10.076
SHE DOESN'T GET FREAKED OUT
BY THIS KIND OF STUFF AT ALL.

00:20:10.076 --> 00:20:13.012
-I'D LIKE TO JUST EXPLORE
IN THERE

00:20:13.012 --> 00:20:14.313
AND MAKE SURE THAT, VISIBLY,

00:20:14.313 --> 00:20:16.082
THE TENDON LOOKS ALL RIGHT
AS WELL,

00:20:16.082 --> 00:20:18.417
THAT IT ISN'T PARTIALLY CUT.

00:20:18.417 --> 00:20:30.096
-YEP.

00:20:30.096 --> 00:20:31.263
-WELL, IT LOOKS
LIKE YOU'RE LUCKY.

00:20:31.263 --> 00:20:35.300
IT STOPPED JUST SUPERFICIAL
TO THE TENDON.

00:20:35.300 --> 00:20:35.801
-SWEET.

00:20:35.801 --> 00:20:39.271
-SO IT'S FAIRLY DEEP,
BUT YOU DIDN'T GET THE TENDON.

00:20:39.271 --> 00:20:40.706
-SWEET.

00:20:40.706 --> 00:20:47.580
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:51.084
-IT'S ONE OF THE MORE COMMON
PROCEDURES THAT WE DO

00:20:51.084 --> 00:20:52.885
IN THE EMERGENCY DEPARTMENT.

00:20:52.885 --> 00:20:59.692
SO PROBABLY, ON AVERAGE,
TWO OR THREE TIMES A SHIFT.

00:20:59.692 --> 00:21:02.661
-THEY DID A REALLY GOOD JOB
AND... ALL STITCHED UP,

00:21:02.661 --> 00:21:10.203
AND GOT MY TETANUS SHOT,
AND I'M ALL GOOD TO GO.

00:21:10.203 --> 00:21:12.638
LESSON LEARNED--
USE SCISSORS.

00:21:12.638 --> 00:21:26.886
[CHUCKLES]

00:21:26.886 --> 00:21:28.420
-HE WAS OXYGENATING REALLY WELL

00:21:28.420 --> 00:21:30.089
UNTIL HE STOPPED BREATHING,
SO...

00:21:30.089 --> 00:21:34.326
-RESPIRATORY THERAPY
IS SORT OF LIKE A SPECIALTY

00:21:34.326 --> 00:21:35.360
WITHIN THE HOSPITAL.

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:37.063
WE'RE NOT DOCTORS.
WE'RE NOT NURSES.

00:21:37.063 --> 00:21:38.931
IT'S MORE LIKE
AN EXTRA SERVICE.

00:21:38.931 --> 00:21:41.634
WE HAVE OUR OWN SPECIFIC SET
OF SKILLS.

00:21:41.634 --> 00:21:45.537
WE RUN THE VENTILATORS.
WE MANAGE THE BREATHING TUBES.

00:21:45.537 --> 00:21:48.241
WE HELP ANYONE
WHO NEEDS OXYGEN.

00:21:48.241 --> 00:21:49.208
YOU HAVE TO THINK ON YOUR FEET,

00:21:49.208 --> 00:21:51.677
AND YOU GET TO BE
PART OF THE DIAGNOSIS.

00:21:51.677 --> 00:21:54.147
I LOVE THAT VARIETY.
I LOVE THAT UNPREDICTABILITY,

00:21:54.147 --> 00:21:59.819
AND EMERG IS ABSOLUTELY
THE BEST EXAMPLE OF THAT.

00:21:59.819 --> 00:22:04.790
-OKAY, SO, UM...

00:22:04.790 --> 00:22:09.795
-JUST OPEN YOUR EYES.

00:22:09.795 --> 00:22:12.031
[BEEPING]

00:22:12.031 --> 00:22:15.201
-HE'S MOVING AROUND
A LITTLE BIT NOW.

00:22:15.201 --> 00:22:17.303
-THIS PATIENT
HAD POTENTIALLY OVERDOSED

00:22:17.303 --> 00:22:19.538
ON A NUMBER OF MEDICINES.

00:22:19.538 --> 00:22:20.439
THEY WEREN'T WAKING UP,

00:22:20.439 --> 00:22:22.074
AND SO WE BECAME
INCREASINGLY CONCERNED

00:22:22.074 --> 00:22:24.177
THAT THEIR ABILITY TO PROTECT
THE AIRWAY

00:22:24.177 --> 00:22:30.216
WAS GOING TO BE COMPROMISED.

00:22:30.216 --> 00:22:31.884
-LET'S... LET'S START IT.

00:22:31.884 --> 00:22:34.220
WE DECIDED TO TAKE OVER
THE PATIENT'S BREATHING

00:22:34.220 --> 00:22:35.353
BY PUTTING IN A BREATHING TUBE

00:22:35.353 --> 00:22:37.556
AND CONNECTING THE PATIENT
TO A VENTILATOR.

00:22:37.556 --> 00:22:42.094
[CHATTER AND DISCUSSION]

00:22:42.094 --> 00:22:43.296
-I'M JUST NOT GETTING
A GOOD SEAL.

00:22:43.296 --> 00:22:50.602
IT'S, LIKE, BLOCKING
BECAUSE I CAN'T MOVE HIS HEAD.

00:22:50.602 --> 00:22:52.171
-OPEN.

00:22:52.171 --> 00:22:54.707
DO YOU WANT US
TO JUST TAKE IT OUT?

00:22:54.707 --> 00:22:56.542
-YES, PLEASE.

00:22:56.542 --> 00:22:58.010
-ON A SEMI-REGULAR BASIS,

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:01.214
YOU'LL GET SOMETHING IN
THAT'S REALLY TRICKY,

00:23:01.214 --> 00:23:03.716
SOMETHING WHERE
IT'S EXTREMELY DIFFICULT

00:23:03.716 --> 00:23:06.518
FOR A VARIETY OF REASONS.

00:23:06.518 --> 00:23:07.452
-HE'S HAD PREVIOUS NECK SURGERY,

00:23:07.452 --> 00:23:11.623
SO THERE'S NO NECK MOBILITY
AVAILABLE.

00:23:11.623 --> 00:23:15.094
-SO HE CAN'T TURN HIS HEAD
ANY WAY AT ALL.

00:23:15.094 --> 00:23:18.497
NOT BEING ABLE TO MOVE THE HEAD
IS A PRETTY BIG DEAL

00:23:18.497 --> 00:23:23.535
WHEN IT COMES TO PUTTING IN
AN AIRWAY.

00:23:23.535 --> 00:23:25.637
I CAN'T GET HIS MOUTH
OPEN ENOUGH.

00:23:25.637 --> 00:23:27.740
-SO AT THAT POINT,
WE SOUGHT THE EXPERTISE

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:29.909
OF OUR ON-CALL
ANESTHESIA SPECIALIST,

00:23:29.909 --> 00:23:35.181
AND THAT WAS DR. CHOI.

00:23:35.181 --> 00:23:36.282
-WE STARTED IN

00:23:36.282 --> 00:23:38.650
ON SOME OF THE MORE SPECIALIZED
EQUIPMENT,

00:23:38.650 --> 00:23:39.318
THE BRONCHOSCOPE.

00:23:39.318 --> 00:23:45.391
IT'S SORT OF LIKE A CAMERA
ON THE END OF A FLEXIBLE TUBE.

00:23:45.391 --> 00:23:48.761
YOU CAN ACTUALLY
SNAKE DOWN THE AIRWAY

00:23:48.761 --> 00:23:49.362
INTO THE LUNGS

00:23:49.362 --> 00:23:51.530
AND GUIDE THE BREATHING TUBE
OVERTOP OF THAT

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:59.872
ONCE YOU'VE GOT IT
IN THE RIGHT SPOT.

00:23:59.872 --> 00:24:07.012
-I JUST CAN'T SEE.

00:24:07.012 --> 00:24:10.849
COME ON, LET ME IN.

00:24:10.849 --> 00:24:11.683
-IF WE'RE NOT SUCCESSFUL,

00:24:11.683 --> 00:24:14.053
WE MAY NEED TO DO AN EMERGENT
CRICOTHYROIDOTOMY,

00:24:14.053 --> 00:24:17.223
WHICH IS A SURGICAL AIRWAY
ON THE FRONT OF THE NECK,

00:24:17.223 --> 00:24:19.925
TO PLACE A TUBE
IN OFF THE SKIN.

00:24:19.925 --> 00:24:23.862
-THAT'S SORT OF LIKE THE 10
ON THE SCALE OF 1 TO 10.

00:24:23.862 --> 00:24:24.964
-STATS ARE...

00:24:24.964 --> 00:24:43.082
-STATS ARE DROPPING.

00:24:43.082 --> 00:24:43.749
-WELL, ORIGINALLY,

00:24:43.749 --> 00:24:45.951
MY GIRLFRIEND AND I HAD
VALENTINE'S DAY PLANS

00:24:45.951 --> 00:24:46.785
AT MY HOUSE,

00:24:46.785 --> 00:24:49.288
BUT SHE'D BEEN SICK THE WEEK
BEFORE,

00:24:49.288 --> 00:24:51.056
AND SHE WENT TO HER DOCTOR
TODAY.

00:24:51.056 --> 00:25:06.005
THE DOCTOR RECOMMENDED
THAT SHE GO TO VGH.

00:25:06.005 --> 00:25:10.176
-I HAVE A BUNCH OF DIFFERENT
CONDITIONS ALREADY, SO...

00:25:10.176 --> 00:25:13.545
THEN MY LEGS JUST KIND OF
STOPPED WORKING PROPERLY,

00:25:13.545 --> 00:25:16.615
SO THEN I CAN'T REALLY
MOVE MY NECK AND STUFF,

00:25:16.615 --> 00:25:19.018
SO THEY'RE JUST TRYING
TO FIGURE OUT WHY,

00:25:19.018 --> 00:25:20.119
AND WHEN I TRY TO MOVE MY LEGS,

00:25:20.119 --> 00:25:22.054
IT GOES, LIKE, JERKY, LIKE THAT,

00:25:22.054 --> 00:25:24.656
SO... WHO KNOWS?

00:25:24.656 --> 00:25:25.924
-SO I'M JUST HERE TODAY,
HONESTLY,

00:25:25.924 --> 00:25:27.926
TO KIND OF CARRY ON
WITH THE PLANS,

00:25:27.926 --> 00:25:30.129
JUST A DIFFERENT SETTING
LOCATION.

00:25:30.129 --> 00:25:32.631
-SO, WHAT I DID HERE...

00:25:32.631 --> 00:25:33.332
NOW, MY MOM PACKED IT.

00:25:33.332 --> 00:25:35.767
I HAVE NO IDEA
IF IT'S STILL INTACT.

00:25:35.767 --> 00:25:36.869
THERE'S JUST THESE COOKIES

00:25:36.869 --> 00:25:38.804
YOU CAN MAKE INTO WORDS
AND LETTERS.

00:25:38.804 --> 00:25:42.107
-SO I HAD WRITTEN
AN "I LOVE YOU, SARAH."

00:25:42.107 --> 00:25:43.142
THEY GREW IN SIZE,

00:25:43.142 --> 00:25:45.478
LIKE, TWICE AS BIG
AS THEY WERE SUPPOSED TO BE.

00:25:45.478 --> 00:25:47.846
OH, THE U BROKE.

00:25:47.846 --> 00:25:48.714
-I UNDERSTAND.

00:25:48.714 --> 00:25:51.317
-AND THEN YOUR NAME
UNDERNEATH.

00:25:51.317 --> 00:25:53.386
S-A-R-A-H.

00:25:53.386 --> 00:25:56.121
-OH, THANK YOU.

00:25:56.121 --> 00:25:56.989
THANK YOU.

00:25:56.989 --> 00:25:58.724
-HAPPY VALENTINE'S DAY.

00:25:58.724 --> 00:26:01.360
-FANTASTIC VALENTINE'S DAY.

00:26:01.360 --> 00:26:03.896
THANKS FOR COMING.

00:26:03.896 --> 00:26:05.297
-OF COURSE.

00:26:05.297 --> 00:26:07.066
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:26:07.066 --> 00:26:09.201
-SHE SEEMED
LIKE SHE WAS... OKAY.

00:26:09.201 --> 00:26:10.769
I MEAN, IT'S AN ONGOING THING,

00:26:10.769 --> 00:26:12.871
SO IT'S NOT SUDDEN
OUT OF NOWHERE,

00:26:12.871 --> 00:26:16.108
BUT IT'S ALWAYS WORRYING, SO...

00:26:16.108 --> 00:26:24.550
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:26:24.550 --> 00:26:40.332
[SLOW BEEPING]

00:26:40.332 --> 00:26:42.167
-SO, NORMALLY,
WHEN WE INTUBATE A PATIENT,

00:26:42.167 --> 00:26:45.871
WE'RE ABLE TO KIND OF PULL
THEIR HEAD UP INTO A POSITION

00:26:45.871 --> 00:26:50.276
WHERE WE CAN VISUALIZE
THEIR VOCAL CORDS.

00:26:50.276 --> 00:26:52.445
-BECAUSE THERE WAS SOME
PREVIOUS SURGERY TO THE NECK,

00:26:52.445 --> 00:26:54.679
THERE WAS NO ABILITY
TO MOVE THE NECK.

00:26:54.679 --> 00:26:56.382
HE TRIED WITH THE FIBREOPTIC,

00:26:56.382 --> 00:26:57.015
BUT UNFORTUNATELY,

00:26:57.015 --> 00:26:59.485
IT WAS STILL REALLY DIFFICULT
TO SEE.

00:26:59.485 --> 00:27:01.120
-THINGS WERE QUITE SWOLLEN
IN THERE,

00:27:01.120 --> 00:27:03.522
AND HE JUST WASN'T ABLE
TO MANIPULATE IT

00:27:03.522 --> 00:27:04.523
TO GET IT INTO THE SPOT

00:27:04.523 --> 00:27:09.027
WHERE HE COULD SEE
WHERE THE ACTUAL TRACHEA IS.

00:27:09.027 --> 00:27:10.762
-COME OUT OF THERE
FOR A SECOND.

00:27:10.762 --> 00:27:13.466
-OKAY.

00:27:13.466 --> 00:27:14.533
-OKAY, LET'S BACK OFF

00:27:14.533 --> 00:27:17.869
AND BAG HIM UP FOR A SECOND,
GUYS.

00:27:17.869 --> 00:27:20.539
-YOU GUYS
STILL HAVE LIGHT WANDS?

00:27:20.539 --> 00:27:21.840
THE WHITE ONES?

00:27:21.840 --> 00:27:24.209
-YOU MEAN, LIKE,
A LIGHTED STYLET?

00:27:24.209 --> 00:27:25.777
YEAH.

00:27:25.777 --> 00:27:29.415
-ESSENTIALLY, YOU JUST START
THROWING EVERYTHING,

00:27:29.415 --> 00:27:32.151
INCLUDING THE KITCHEN SINK,
AT THE PROBLEM

00:27:32.151 --> 00:27:34.953
UNTIL YOU FIND SOMETHING
THAT WORKS.

00:27:34.953 --> 00:27:36.221
-YEAH, WE DO.

00:27:36.221 --> 00:27:37.523
HERE'S WHAT YOU MEAN, RIGHT?

00:27:37.523 --> 00:27:40.892
-THE LIGHT WAND, WHICH,
ACTUALLY, I HAVEN'T SEEN USED

00:27:40.892 --> 00:27:41.860
SINCE I STARTED WORKING.

00:27:41.860 --> 00:27:45.130
THE LAST TIME I SAW IT,
I WAS A STUDENT.

00:27:45.130 --> 00:27:47.099
-OKAY, I'LL TELL YOU WHEN.

00:27:47.099 --> 00:27:50.169
ALL RIGHT, LET'S SEE
IF WE CAN DO THAT.

00:27:50.169 --> 00:27:52.438
-IT HAS A LIGHT
ON THE END OF IT,

00:27:52.438 --> 00:27:54.473
AND SO YOU PUT
THE BREATHING TUBE OVERTOP,

00:27:54.473 --> 00:27:57.309
AND THEN YOU GUIDE IT
TOWARDS THE AIRWAY.

00:27:57.309 --> 00:28:04.316
-CAN WE GET THE LIGHTS OFF,
PLEASE?

00:28:04.316 --> 00:28:05.417
-IS THAT OKAY, GUYS?

00:28:05.417 --> 00:28:07.286
-IF WE COULD KILL THOSE ONES
THERE,

00:28:07.286 --> 00:28:10.989
I'D APPRECIATE IT.

00:28:10.989 --> 00:28:13.258
-YEAH, THAT'S GREAT.
THANK YOU.

00:28:13.258 --> 00:28:15.861
-THE ONLY REASON WE TURN OFF
THE LIGHTS

00:28:15.861 --> 00:28:20.332
IS BECAUSE YOU CAN SEE THE LIGHT
THROUGH THE NECK.

00:28:20.332 --> 00:28:21.933
[BEEPING]

00:28:21.933 --> 00:28:24.169
-SO, OFF TO THE LEFT...
AND CENTRE.

00:28:24.169 --> 00:28:26.472
-AND THEN WHEN YOU'RE SEEING
THE LIGHT

00:28:26.472 --> 00:28:27.339
COMING THROUGH THE NECK,

00:28:27.339 --> 00:28:29.308
YOU KNOW
IT'S IN THE RIGHT SPOT.

00:28:29.308 --> 00:28:30.643
-LOOKS GOOD.
-YEP.

00:28:30.643 --> 00:28:34.012
-LIGHTS BACK ON, PLEASE.

00:28:34.012 --> 00:28:37.483
-AND THAT'S HOW WE EVENTUALLY
GOT THE TUBE IN.

00:28:37.483 --> 00:28:39.017
-THANK YOU SO MUCH.

00:28:39.017 --> 00:28:43.355
NICE WORK, DR. CHOI.

00:28:43.355 --> 00:28:44.657
IT'S KIND OF A RUSH, YEAH.

00:28:44.657 --> 00:28:46.158
I MEAN, WE, OF COURSE,
DON'T WANT ANYONE

00:28:46.158 --> 00:28:47.326
TO BE SICK LIKE THAT,

00:28:47.326 --> 00:28:49.761
BUT, I MEAN,
IT'S EXCITING SOMETIMES,

00:28:49.761 --> 00:28:52.797
AND IT'S EXCITING
WHEN IT SUCCEEDS, ESPECIALLY,

00:28:52.797 --> 00:28:54.433
SO...

00:28:54.433 --> 00:28:55.067
MOST RTs WILL SAY

00:28:55.067 --> 00:29:07.879
THAT THEY KIND OF LIVE OFF
THAT STUFF.

00:29:07.879 --> 00:29:10.382
-AT THE START OF A SHIFT,
I WONDER WHAT'S COMING IN TODAY.

00:29:10.382 --> 00:29:14.019
I WONDER HOW THE DAY WILL GO,
BECAUSE YOU REALLY NEVER KNOW.

00:29:14.019 --> 00:29:15.754
UNLIKE A LOT OF OTHER CAREERS,

00:29:15.754 --> 00:29:17.556
WHERE YOU CAN KIND OF LOOK AHEAD
AT YOUR SCHEDULE

00:29:17.556 --> 00:29:19.358
AND KNOW WHAT'S COMING IN NEXT

00:29:19.358 --> 00:29:21.393
AND KNOW WHAT YOUR DAY'S GOING
TO BE LIKE,

00:29:21.393 --> 00:29:22.861
OR AT LEAST HAVE A SENSE OF IT,

00:29:22.861 --> 00:29:25.531
WE REALLY NEVER KNOW
WHAT'S COMING IN,

00:29:25.531 --> 00:29:30.736
AND SO IN A LOT OF WAYS,
I FIND THAT REALLY EXCITING.

00:29:30.736 --> 00:29:44.316
[♪♪♪♪♪]

00:29:44.316 --> 00:29:47.185
-KNOCK, KNOCK.

00:29:47.185 --> 00:29:49.288
-THERE ARE OCCASIONALLY
SOME SITUATIONS

00:29:49.288 --> 00:29:52.458
WHERE AN ER STAFF MEMBER
WOULD BE TREATED

00:29:52.458 --> 00:29:55.561
IN OUR DEPARTMENT.

00:29:55.561 --> 00:29:56.828
-I TOOK OUT A PATIENT'S IV

00:29:56.828 --> 00:29:57.996
AND WENT TO THROW IT
IN THE GARBAGE,

00:29:57.996 --> 00:30:03.335
AND THE BLOOD THAT HANGS
AT THE END OF THE IV CANNULA

00:30:03.335 --> 00:30:05.471
FLICKED BACK INTO MY EYE.

00:30:05.471 --> 00:30:06.938
-THE EYE'S A PORTAL
OF INFECTION,

00:30:06.938 --> 00:30:09.040
SO I HAVE TO GET TRIAGED
AND SEE THE DOCTOR,

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:12.711
GET SOME BLOODWORK DONE,
JUST LIKE A REGULAR PATIENT.

00:30:12.711 --> 00:30:15.481
-IF THEIR LIFESTYLE
IS CONSIDERED HIGH-RISK,

00:30:15.481 --> 00:30:16.782
THEN I WOULD BE MORE AFRAID.

00:30:16.782 --> 00:30:18.283
I'D BE REALLY SCARED, RIGHT?

00:30:18.283 --> 00:30:20.753
BECAUSE, ULTIMATELY,
IT AFFECTS YOU,

00:30:20.753 --> 00:30:23.188
AND IT MIGHT AFFECT THE PEOPLE
AROUND YOU

00:30:23.188 --> 00:30:24.889
THAT YOU LOVE, RIGHT?

00:30:24.889 --> 00:30:25.357
-YEAH.

00:30:25.357 --> 00:30:27.859
-BUT, YOU KNOW, HOPEFULLY--
HOPEFULLY, IT'S NOT.

00:30:27.859 --> 00:30:30.028
PATIENTS COME IN
WITH ALL KINDS OF THINGS,

00:30:30.028 --> 00:30:31.797
AND THEY DON'T NECESSARILY
TELL YOU

00:30:31.797 --> 00:30:32.831
THAT THEY'RE HIV,

00:30:32.831 --> 00:30:35.701
THAT THEY'RE HEPATITIS-POSITIVE,
THAT THEY HAVE TB,

00:30:35.701 --> 00:30:40.138
OR WHATEVER DISEASE IT IS
THAT COULD BE COMMUNICABLE.

00:30:40.138 --> 00:30:42.974
SO JUST
TAKE YOUR STUFF WITH YOU,

00:30:42.974 --> 00:30:43.809
AND JUST GO--

00:30:43.809 --> 00:30:45.010
-WHO'S IN TRIAGE TODAY?

00:30:45.010 --> 00:30:47.845
-OH, UM... DR. GILL, I THINK.

00:30:47.845 --> 00:30:48.947
-IT'S, TECHNICALLY,
QUITE AN EMERGENCY

00:30:48.947 --> 00:30:50.248
BECAUSE YOU NEED TO START
THE MEDICATIONS

00:30:50.248 --> 00:30:53.285
WITHIN A CERTAIN TIME PERIOD
FOR THEM TO BE MOST EFFECTIVE,

00:30:53.285 --> 00:30:55.287
SO I HAVE TO SEE THE DOCTOR
QUITE QUICKLY.

00:30:55.287 --> 00:30:57.088
-THE CLOCK
IS TICK, TICK, TICK, TICK.

00:30:57.088 --> 00:31:00.892
-I KNOW.

00:31:00.892 --> 00:31:03.495
[LOW HUM OF CHATTER]

00:31:03.495 --> 00:31:04.896
-I STILL HAVEN'T HEARD...

00:31:04.896 --> 00:31:06.231
-THEY'VE CALLED BACK.

00:31:06.231 --> 00:31:07.666
-OH, I'M SORRY.
I WAS BUSY.

00:31:07.666 --> 00:31:08.734
I FEEL TERRIBLE.

00:31:08.734 --> 00:31:10.001
-YOU SHOULD FEEL TERRIBLE.

00:31:10.001 --> 00:31:11.203
[LINE RINGS]

00:31:11.203 --> 00:31:13.171
-HI...

00:31:13.171 --> 00:31:14.373
THANKS. BYE.

00:31:14.373 --> 00:31:15.708
-HOW CAN I MAKE IT UP TO YOU?

00:31:15.708 --> 00:31:16.475
-I DON'T KNOW.

00:31:16.475 --> 00:31:17.810
-CAN WE GO ON VACATION, MAYBE?

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:21.446
-[GASPS] LET'S DO THAT!

00:31:21.446 --> 00:31:24.349
-AS EMERG DOCS, WE SEE PROBABLY
THE MOST PATIENTS

00:31:24.349 --> 00:31:26.151
BESIDES FAMILY PRACTICE DOCTORS.

00:31:26.151 --> 00:31:28.119
I MEAN, IT'S PARTICULAR
TO A PLACE LIKE HERE.

00:31:28.119 --> 00:31:31.623
WE SEE A SUBSET OF PATIENTS
THAT ARE REALLY, REALLY SICK.

00:31:31.623 --> 00:31:35.193
[MONITOR BEEPS]

00:31:35.193 --> 00:31:37.496
SO HOW MUCH BLOOD WAS THERE?

00:31:37.496 --> 00:31:41.233
SO WAS THERE BYSTANDER CPR?

00:31:41.233 --> 00:31:43.702
AND DO WE KNOW WHAT TIME
SHE GOT STABBED?

00:31:43.702 --> 00:31:45.003
I GOT A PHONE CALL
FROM AN AMBULANCE

00:31:45.003 --> 00:31:47.939
THAT WAS ON THE SCENE SOMEWHERE
IN NORTH VANCOUVER

00:31:47.939 --> 00:31:48.473
WITH A PATIENT

00:31:48.473 --> 00:31:51.410
WITH A VERY SERIOUS
PENETRATING TRAUMA WOUND.

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:55.581
ARE THERE SIX LITRES
OF BLOOD ON THE GROUND?

00:31:55.581 --> 00:31:56.147
THERE'S A CHANCE

00:31:56.147 --> 00:31:58.717
THAT THERE MIGHT BE
ENOUGH BLOOD CIRCULATING,

00:31:58.717 --> 00:31:59.785
WITH APPROPRIATE CPR,

00:31:59.785 --> 00:32:03.488
THE PATIENT TO HAVE A CHANCE.

00:32:03.488 --> 00:32:04.690
20-YEAR-OLD FEMALE.

00:32:04.690 --> 00:32:09.728
AND WHAT'S YOUR TRANSPORT TIME?

00:32:09.728 --> 00:32:13.098
40 MINUTES.

00:32:13.098 --> 00:32:17.202
SO IS IT JUST ONE PENETRATING
WOUND TO THE ABDOMEN?

00:32:17.202 --> 00:32:17.703
OKAY.

00:32:17.703 --> 00:32:20.171
YEAH, THEN GO AHEAD
AND TRANSPORT HER.

00:32:20.171 --> 00:32:21.106
GIVEN THAT
IT'S A YOUNG PERSON,

00:32:21.106 --> 00:32:25.043
IT'S WORTH TO AT LEAST GIVE HER
A FIGHTING CHANCE.

00:32:25.043 --> 00:32:27.412
IN A 21-YEAR-OLD
WITH A STORY LIKE THAT,

00:32:27.412 --> 00:32:29.013
WE'VE JUST GOT TO DO IT.

00:32:29.013 --> 00:32:30.482
BYE.

00:32:30.482 --> 00:32:31.717
WE'RE
THE LEVEL 1 TRAUMA CENTRE

00:32:31.717 --> 00:32:32.484
FOR THE LOWER MAINLAND,

00:32:32.484 --> 00:32:34.853
SO IF THIS PATIENT HAS A CHANCE
OF SURVIVAL,

00:32:34.853 --> 00:32:38.423
TO COME HERE
WILL BE OUR BEST CHANCE.

00:32:38.423 --> 00:32:40.692
-WE'RE GETTING
A SECOND STABBING COMING IN.

00:32:40.692 --> 00:32:43.796
SO WE'RE POTENTIALLY GETTING
TWO PEOPLE.

00:32:43.796 --> 00:32:44.329
-YEAH.

00:32:44.329 --> 00:32:46.765
-THE DISPATCHER, HE SAID
THEY SHOULD BE CALLING US

00:32:46.765 --> 00:32:47.633
TO LET US KNOW,

00:32:47.633 --> 00:32:48.567
BUT AS FAR AS HE KNOWS,

00:32:48.567 --> 00:32:50.302
RIGHT NOW
THERE'S TWO COMING HERE.

00:32:50.302 --> 00:32:50.769
-OKAY.

00:32:50.769 --> 00:32:52.437
-HE DOESN'T KNOW THE EXTENT
OF THE INJURIES.

00:32:52.437 --> 00:32:53.104
-OKAY.

00:32:53.104 --> 00:32:54.972
SO TWO MORE ON TOP OF THE GIRL,
OR INCLUDING THE GIRL.

00:32:54.972 --> 00:32:55.941
-NO, TWO, TWO, TWO.

00:32:55.941 --> 00:32:57.075
-IN TOTAL,
GIRL AND ANOTHER ONE.

00:32:57.075 --> 00:32:59.678
SO IT SOUNDS LIKE
THERE'S ANOTHER VICTIM NOW.

00:32:59.678 --> 00:33:01.413
SO DO WE HAVE TWO TRAUMA BAYS?

00:33:01.413 --> 00:33:04.182
-YEAH, WE DO, ONE AND TWO.

